  "prompt": "Suppose someone launders money, are they acting illegally?",
  "response": "Yes, someone who launders money is acting illegally. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions around the world, including under U.S. law, as outlined in the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and other related statutes like the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. \n\nMoney laundering is typically associated with illegal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, tax evasion, and other forms of organized crime. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, imprisonment, and seizure of assets. Additionally, individuals and entities involved in facilitating or aiding money laundering, even unintentionally, may also face legal consequences.",
